effective group name. Selection by session is specified by many standards, but selection by effective group is the logical behavior that several other operating systems use. by parent process ID. This selects the processes with a parent process ID in pidlist. That is, it selects processes that are children of those listed in pidlist.
This selects the processes with a session ID specified in sesslist.
If the column width cannot show all signals, the column will end with a plus "+". Columns with only a hyphen have no signals.

sorting order. Sorting syntax is [+|-]key[,[+|-]key[,...]]. Choose a multi-letter key from the STANDARD FORMAT SPECIFIERS section. The "+" is optional since default direction is increasing numerical or lexicographic order. Identical to k. For example: ps jax --sort=uid,-ppid, +pid
Identical to -t and t.
Identical to -u and U.
Select all processes. Identical to -e.

by command name. This selects the processes whose executable name is given in cmdlist. NOTE: The command name is not the same as the command line. Previous versions of procps and the kernel truncated this command name to 15 characters. This limitation is no longer present in both. If you depended on matching only 15 characters, you may no longer get a match.
This format is parsed by strftime(3) and should be a maximum of 24 characters to not mis-align columns.

This selects the processes whose process ID numbers appear in pidlist. Identical to p and --pid.

This selects the processes whose process ID numbers appear in pidlist. With this option ps reads the necessary info only for the pids listed in the pidlist and doesn't apply additional filtering rules. The order of pids is unsorted and preserved. No additional selection options, sorting and forest type listings are allowed in this mode. Identical to q and --quick-pid.
only running processes

This selects the processes associated with the terminals given in ttylist. Terminals (ttys, or screens for text output) can be specified in several forms: /dev/ttyS1, ttyS1, S1. A plain "-" may be used to select processes not attached to any terminal.
by effective user ID (EUID) or name. This selects the processes whose effective user name or ID is in userlist.

Do not show flags; show rss in place of addr. This option can only be used with -l.
